title: For Sale:  German Gewehr 98 Amberg 8mm Mauser
postcontent: All parts are matching, including the cleaning rod and stock. The mechanics are excellent and the bore is very fine. The stock is fine. This rifle has the initials "EWB" (EinwohnerWehrBayarn) burned into the right side of the butt, indicating service with the Freikorps just after the war. The Freikorps were mercenary units in Germany, made up of returning veterans, who fought to put down Communist uprisings. They were officially disbanded in 1920, deemed a violation of the Treaty of Versailles. Original, WWI, German Gewehr 98 manufactured at Amberg Arsenal in 1917. Chambered for the 7.92x57mm cartridge (8mm Mauser), The Gew. 98 was the standard German Infantry Weapon of the First World War. This rifle is in very fine condition with about 95% of its factory blued finish remaining and an arsenal bright bolt. No pitting. It is well marked with acceptance stamps.

location: North Carolina, North Carolina, United States
postcontent: New In Box (never fired). This polymer FN Herstal Five-Seven MKII is chambered for 5.7x28mm with Adjustable sights. It features a 4.41” barrel, an overall length of 8.2”, and an ambidextrous manual safety. Includes: FN Herstal Hard Case, Operator's Instructions Manual/paperwork, FNH Pistol Lock, factory test casing, (3) 20 round magazines, and (1) 30 round magazine. PLUS, 1000 rounds RARE FN ammo = 550 rounds SS195LF HOT ammo (11 Boxes of 50 rounds per/box) and 450 rounds RARE SS192 "Green Ammo" (9 Boxes of 50 rounds per/box). RARE SS192 “Green Ammo” was produced for ONLY 3 months before FN turned to the SS195LF. The SS192 "Green Ammo" is the predecessor to the current SS195LF which uses the same 27gr HP aluminum core bullet but with a lead free primer, hence the LF designation. The SS192 “green ammo” or environmentally friendly ammo was SS195LF ammo before they changed the name and box. The manufacture (FN Herstal) relates the labeling as a way to visibly mark the packaging so that there is a lower chance for this to be mixed up with SS192 ammunition that contains lead primer.

Please click link below http://blackwolfsupply.com/index.php/product/bravo-company-charging-handle-moda44-5-56mm223-ambidextrous-black-finish-gfh-556-mod-a44/ Description Bravo Company, Charging Handle, MODA44, 5.56MM/223, Ambidextrous, Black Finish This is the AMBIDEXTROUS version of the  BCMGUNFIGHTER CHARGING HANDLE A Charging Handle for the 21st Century Gun Fighter A NEW Charging Handle and Extended Latch System Charging Handle forged from 7075 T6 Aluminum Hard Coat Anodized per Mil-A-8625F, Type III, Class 2 GFH – Mod3 (large latch) and Mod4 (medium latch) Compatible with Mil-Spec AR-15 Direct Impingement Weapon Systems. **NOT compatible with adjustable gas keyed bolt carrier groups.** VLTOR US Pat No. 8104393, 8336436, 8356537 When the AR15 system was first introduced to and fielded by the US Military in the 1960s, the manual of arms for an infantryman was significantly different than what currently exists today. To charge the rifle the shooter released their hand from a firing grip, grabbed each side of the charging handle with the thumb and forefinger or the first two fingers , (while applying pressure to the latch) pulled the charging handle all the way to the rear, and then released it to charge the weapon. Like everything else in the last 45 years, tactics and weaponry have undergone a continuous evolution. Red dot optics get the shooter on target quicker, shorter barrels allow the operator to more quickly negotiate tighter urban areas, and operator’s manipulations of the weapon system have become much more efficient and faster. The current manual of arms has the operator maintaining a firing grip almost continuously while manipulating the weapon with the non-dominant hand in an effort to more quickly get the weapon ready to fire. With that premise, most weapon manipulations are done only with the shooter’s support hand; to include operating the charging handle. In order to perform an immediate action or charge the carbine, current CQB techniques have the operator racking the charging handle to the rear using their support side hand only. This is done in one swift and strong movement. With the operator’s firing grip maintained, the weapon again has a loaded chamber, and the shooter can immediately bring a hot weapon back into the fight. The BCMGUNFIGHTER™ Charging Handle and extended latches feature internal redesigns to direct the force off of the roll pin and into the body of the charging handle during support hand only manipulations. This new design has a built in backstop engineered into the extended latch and into the charging handle. As the latch is opened up, its’ travel is limited by these flat surface backstops. With this travel limiting feature, the stress is taken off the roll pin, and is now redirected into the entire body of the charging handle. The BCMGUNFIGHTER™ Charging Handle offers two significant advantages.   Since the tiny roll pin is no longer the weak point – it is a much stronger system and tactical latch will stay intact even under repeated support side only manipulation.   With the force kept inside the body of the handle, when the handle is pulled directly to the rear, it moves directly to the rear and does not angle off to the outboard side. A much smoother operation.   https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MXNEvEvA4Fc&feature=youtu.be   Product Specifications   UPC Code: 855877004039   Manufacturer: Bravo Company   Manufacturer Part #: GFH 556 MOD A44   Model: Mod A44   Model: 5.56MM/223   Type: Charging Handle   Finish/Color: Black   Description: Ambidextrious Charging Handle   Subcategory: Long Gun Parts
